english:
  title: 'Epitaph for the Gyerim Prefectural Prince, Posthumously Honored as the Sage of Integrity: A Memorial Inscription with Preface'
  author: Lee In-bok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the spring of the Year of the Metal Ox under the Zhizheng reign, the great minister of our state, Chamberlain of Consensus Wang, entered the capital to pay homage at the imperial court. That autumn, in the seventh month on the day of guimsi, as he returned and reached Changyi County, he fell gravely ill. The envoy of the Liaodong region transmitted his remains homeward. The scholars and officials all came to pay their respects. Not a child in the streets nor a woman in the alleys failed to cry out in wonder. Among the people of the four directions, there were those who wept in anguish. The king thereupon granted him the posthumous name Sage of Integrity, and commanded the officials to conduct his funeral rites with proper ceremony. In the ninth month on the day of xinyu, he was laid to rest in the original grounds of the Baek-wood Valley in Imjin County.

    Three months before these events, the Marquis of Gimhae, the Sage of Yigjae, called to me and said: "Alas, this noble lord was the brother of my departed wife. How could I bear to inscribe his epitaph? I ask that you gather the greatest deeds of his life, carve them upon stone, and preserve them in the vault. This too shall be as my own inscription." I, In-bok, having once received this noble's patronage, could not refuse. Let me set forth what I have learned:

    The lord was a native of Bokju in Gyeongsang Province. His great-grandfather, whose name was Wae, served as Judge of the Imperial Stables and Scholar of the Hall of Scholarly Worthies. His grandfather, whose name was Hwon, held the rank of Counselor and Judge of the Bureau of Rites in retirement, and received the posthumous name of Clarity. His father, whose name was Pu, was the Marquis of Yonggahoe with the posthumous name of Integrity. His mother was of the Yu clan, the Grand Lady of Ban.

    The lord was born in the year of the Fire Monkey under the Great Virtue reign. In childhood, he spoke seldom and smiled not at all, avoiding all childish play, and was unlike his brothers. His mother marveled at his nature. His elder brother, the Marquis of Gilchang, had received the favor of King Chungseon. When the king inquired after the brothers and heard of this one's name, he rejoiced. Before he could even summon him, he granted him the rank of Commander. Soon he was advanced to Judge of the Three Ministries. At fourteen or fifteen years of age, he undertook weighty responsibilities, and his colleagues marveled at his wisdom.

    In the year of xin-hai, the king summoned him from the imperial court, and upon seeing him once, adopted him as a son. His affection was boundless and his care complete. In the summer of gui-chou, the lord followed the king back to our realm. He rode always in the same carriage as the king. Rising from Vice Director of the Imperial Stables, he advanced to Censor of the Palace. The following year he was promoted to Grand Commandant of the Third Order and created Marquis of Gyerim, his name recorded in the royal genealogy.

    When the king returned to the imperial court, he memorialized that the lord be made attendant to the Crown Prince, granted the rank of Marquis of Gyerim with the noble title of Grand Master of Ceremony. Immediately the king purchased lands and estates for him in the capital to bestow upon him. In the early years of Emperor Yingzong's reign, the eunuch Bayang Dugusi held imperial favor and brought calumny against the king, so that he was condemned to travel westward. The lord, with unwavering devotion, even offered himself in the king's stead. When the emperor heard this, he pitied him deeply, and the eunuch could not harm him.

    In the winter of gui-hai, the lord set forth with two or three companions of the household, intending to visit the king's place of exile. Upon the road he met an imperial envoy traveling westward. They spoke together, and the envoy rejoiced, saying: "I bear an imperial decree to summon the king home. I must make circuits through many provinces, which may delay me. Would that you go ahead and announce this glad news." He gave the lord three relay horses, and the lord rode day and night until he reached the king at Linzhao. Soon thereafter the envoy arrived, and together they escorted the king to the capital at the very beginning of Emperor Taiding's reign.

    At that time King Chungsuk remained long at court and could not return. The Shen Wang harbored secret ambitions and devised a hundred stratagems, while the king could neither confirm nor deny. Many around him were fickle, but the lord alone held fast to righteousness, never speaking words of division from first to last. In the fifth month of yi-chou, the king passed away in the imperial capital. The lord donned the coarse mourning cloth and brought the royal cortege back to our realm. After the burial, on the first and fifteenth days of each month, he privately made offerings at the tomb, continuing this until his own death. He also restored the Haian Temple near the royal grave, that merit might be offered for the king's peace in the spirit realm.

    The king had once begun copying the Sutra of Six Hundred Pratimoksha in gold and silver dust but completed less than half. The lord, using his own resources, finished the sacred work. Twenty years passed after the king's passing without a posthumous name being granted. The lord entered the imperial court and petitioned for the king's title, and also for King Chungsuk's name. Though those wielding power offered little assistance, the lord considered it his own responsibility. He spared no expense until at last the petition was granted.

    In the autumn of ga-shen, the Grand Lady of Ban passed away. That winter, the late king appointed the lord Counselor of the Right and Minister of Consensus, though the Marquis of Yongga yet lived. When pressed repeatedly, the lord reluctantly took office and began his governance. First he returned the selection process to the Bureau of Military Records. In former times the judges' stipends were meager, so lands and serfs in the Gyeonggi region were granted as salary supplements called the Salary Fields. Powerful nobles had seized nearly all of these, and the various noble households suffered greatly. The lord issued an edict restoring them. Those officials of talent and virtue he supported with strength. With the treacherous and corrupt he would not even converse. Before long he was dismissed from office.

    In the winter of bing-xu, an imperial decree summoned him to the palace, delegating to him the work of administration and reform. The Vice Minister of the Capital clung stubbornly to his own views and thought it shameful to consult with others. When officials of the court came to inquire, only the lord was entrusted with the matter. In the spring of wu-zi, he became Minister again. The capital fell into great famine. Yangguang Province and the Western Sea region suffered most severely. The lord opened the storehouses and distributed grain for relief. Countless people were saved from starvation through his mercy.

    The lord's nature was steadfast and solemn, dignified and weighty. His countenance was noble and his bearing upright, so that to look upon him inspired respect and awe. Yet within his breast there was no hidden scheme or stratagem. Throughout his life he spoke no careless word. Though his reading was not extensive, he grasped the great principles and could discourse upon the deeds of the ancient sages. He delighted in receiving guests and treated even the humblest scholar with full courtesy. His nature was austere and frugal, without material desire. Though he served King Chungseon for many years, he never once sought private audience on personal matters.

    During his three years in high office, he raised the worthy and capable, relieved the people's suffering, and curtailed wasteful expenditure. In all matters that could bring benefit or eliminate harm, he spared no effort. Save for banquets and court attendance, he sat in his study, pondering the state's affairs with such intensity that he sometimes forgot to eat. Through his virtue, both the inner censorate and the outer provincial governors came to understand his will and strengthened their integrity. No corrupt governance or harsh taxation reached the common people. Many who had fled their homes in despair now returned.

    When entrusted with the work of reform, litigation flowed like a swarm of bees, yet he judged all cases according to law alone. Not even kinsmen or old friends received leniency. Such great impartiality and righteousness flowed from his very nature. Surely one such as this deserves to be called a true great minister!

    The lord's wife was of the Hong clan, daughter of the Prime Minister Seon. His daughter married an imperial Censor and Controller. His son, Jungwi, held the rank of Commander and remained unmarried. The lord was originally of the Kwon clan with the personal name Jae. His name was changed to Wang Hu, a gift from King Chungseon. His childhood name was Talwhan.

    The inscription reads:

    *Alas, this noble lord held our nation's fate,*
    *Born of mountain essence, he soared toward the stars.*
    *A virtuous man's bearing, a sage's gentle word,*
    *In youth he won the Sage King's deepest trust.*
    *Like his own son the king cherished him with love,*
    *And in his teachings mirrored such affection.*
    *Through grace and honor in two realms he rose so high,*
    *With loyalty and filial piety unstained throughout his life.*
    *His heart delighted ever in the worthy and the good,*
    *Twice raised to minister, he saved the suffering multitude.*
    *When Heaven's edict came to order the Eastern land,*
    *Alone he held the state's great cause with steadfast faith.*
    *Like stone unmoved when torrents rush and roar,*
    *One pillar held the great house from the floor.*
    *Yi Yin's sacred charge, Yan Zhu's noble way—*
    *Of hundred deeds performed, he gave but one away.*
    *Yet Heaven, unmoved, drew back His hand so soon,*
    *And gentlemen now mourn as did for Zichan's tomb.*
    *Such virtue as this lord possessed was rare in ancient days,*
    *Mark well this stone—his legacy forever stays.*
